        "client_msg_id": "24c3f0a0-34fc-4c4b-a5fd-09cce03e3476",
        "type": "message",
        "text": "Modes in the broad sense are unavoidable so we have to figure out how to wrangle them. Even in non-modal text editors, if I open the File menu I'm now in a 'mini mode' where I can't just type what I want. If I open a command palette, that's another mini mode. Dialog boxes are no different.\n\nTed Nelson observed in one of his talks something to the effect of \"applications are the ultimate mode\" - talking about how each application is a mode in itself. The Photoshop mode on my computer works very different from the gmail mode, etc.",
        "user": "U8A5MS6R1",
        "ts": "1607663827.259000",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "cTpV",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Modes in the broad sense are unavoidable so we have to figure out how to wrangle them. Even in non-modal text editors, if I open the File menu I'm now in a 'mini mode' where I can't just type what I want. If I open a command palette, that's another mini mode. Dialog boxes are no different.\n\nTed Nelson observed in one of his talks something to the effect of \"applications are the ultimate mode\" - talking about how each application is a mode in itself. The Photoshop mode on my computer works very different from the gmail mode, etc."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
