        "client_msg_id": "4980188c-5176-44cc-a7af-5684bd0141a5",
        "type": "message",
        "text": "The best demodifying I've seen is in the Civilization series of games.  At the start of your turn, a bunch of things request your attention, \"Okay, boss, what do I do now?\"\n\nOriginally, it was one modal dialog after another.  A decision might require looking at the state of the map \u2014 unavailable since the mode had hijacked the UI.  Late in the game at dozens of modal windows would show up before you could check, so you might adopt the strategy of making a silly choice as a signifier that you need to come back to it.\n\nIn the latest Civ games (can't recall when exactly), instead of the modal hijack, you get a to-do list at the start of every turn.  When you're good and ready you can pick an item, and if after looking you decide you weren't as good and ready as you thought, you can escape and look around more.",
        "user": "UA14TGLTC",
        "ts": "1607664165.259200",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "pKcM2",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "The best demodifying I've seen is in the Civilization series of games.  At the start of your turn, a bunch of things request your attention, \"Okay, boss, what do I do now?\"\n\nOriginally, it was one modal dialog after another.  A decision might require looking at the state of the map \u2014 unavailable since the mode had hijacked the UI.  Late in the game at dozens of modal windows would show up before you could check, so you might adopt the strategy of making a silly choice as a signifier that you need to come back to it.\n\nIn the latest Civ games (can't recall when exactly), instead of the modal hijack, you get a to-do list at the start of every turn.  When you're good and ready you can pick an item, and if after looking you decide you weren't as good and ready as you thought, you can escape and look around more."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ],
